rtley in Devon, Hampshire, and Kent, and from Hartleigh in Devon. Similar placenames occur in Berkshire, Dorset, and Northumberland, but it is not known if they gave rise to surnames. Most of the placenames derive from Old English <i>heorot</i> ‘hart, stag’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’, though the Westmorland placename comes from Old English <i>heard</i> ‘hard’ + <i>clā</i> ‘claw, tongue of land’, and the Northumberland placename derives from Old English <i>heorot</i> + <i>hlāw</i> ‘mound, hill’.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hArtghaile</b> ‘descendant of <i>Artghal</i>’, a personal name composed of the elements <i>Art</i> ‘bear’ or ‘hero’ + <i>gal</i> ‘valor’."],"variants":[{"name":"Artley","meanings":["English: variant of   Hartley   with loss of initial <i>H-</i>."]},{"name":"Hartless","meanings":["English (Staffordshire): variant of   Hartley   or of   Hartle  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. The spelling of the modern surname is no doubt due to confusion with the English vocabulary word <i>heartless</i>, meaning ‘cruel or unfeeling’."]}]},{"name":"Katherine","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: Same as Catherine."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Katherine Hartley was born about 1250. She married Thomas de Peniston III. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters."},"et":{"about 1250–":"umbes 1250–Surnud","1245–1269":"1245–1269","1270–Male":"1270–Surnud","1635–Female":"1635–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1250–Female":"1250–Surnud","25 Mar 1635":"25. märts 1635","1635":"1635","about 1250":"umbes 1250","1269":"1269","1245":"1245","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","Nettleham, Lincoln, England":"Nettleham, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1250–":"noin 1250–Kuollut","1245–1269":"1245–1269","1270–Male":"1270–Kuollut","1635–Female":"1635–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1250–Female":"1250–Kuollut","25 Mar 1635":"25. maaliskuuta 1635","1635":"1635","about 1250":"noin 1250","1269":"1269","1245":"1245","1250":"1250","